Module mesakit.map.geography
Package com.telenav.mesakit.map.geography

Class Location

java.lang.Object
com.telenav.mesakit.map.geography.Location
All Implemented Interfaces:
com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.model.Identifiable, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.numeric.DoubleQuantizable, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.numeric.Quantizable, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.string.Stringable, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.string.StringSource, com.telenav.kivakit.validation.Validatable, Located, LocationSequence, Bounded, Intersectable, Serializable
Direct Known Subclasses:
LocatedHeading, PolylineSnap
public class Location extends Object implements com.telenav.kivakit.validation.Validatable, Located, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.model.Identifiable, Bounded, Intersectable, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.string.Stringable, Serializable
Representation of a location on the globe in terms of latitude and longitude. Locations are stored internally in Precision.DM7. Locations can be created in several different ways:
  • degrees(double, double)
  • dm5(int, int)
  • dm5(long)
  • dm6(int, int)
  • dm6(long)
  • dm7(int, int)
  • dm7(long)

The methods that construct from different decimal precisions come in two forms, the first taking two integers representing latitude and longitude in the given precision, the second taking a single long. This long value is composed of a high int and a low int storing the latitude and longitude in DM7 precision. The two values can be retrieved with latitude(long) and longitude(long).

A location value can be converted in the other direction from two DM7 values into a single long value with toLong(int, int), or a location object can convert itself into a long value with asLong() or asLong(Precision) if a particular precision is desired. There are also convenience methods for each precision: asDm5Long(), asDm6Long() and asDm7Long().

New locations can also be derived from an existing location object in several ways:

  • moved(Heading, Distance) - This location moved the given distance at the given heading
  • scaledBy(double, double) - This location multiplied by the given scale factors
  • offsetBy(Width) - This location offset by the given Width
  • offsetBy(Height) - This location offset by the given Height
  • minus(Width) - This location offset by the given Width
  • minus(Height) - This location offset by the given Height

The distance between two locations can be computed in three different ways

  • haversineDistanceTo(Location)
  • lawOfCosinesDistanceTo(Location)
  • equirectangularDistanceTo(Location)
The haversine and cosines methods are both fairly accurate at any latitude for any distance. The equirectangular distance formula is accurate enough only for locations that span a relatively "small" amount of latitude distance (less than a few tens of kilometers). However, the equirectangular distance formula is much faster than the more accurate methods, so it is the method used in distanceTo(Location) when the latitude separation is small and when it is large distanceTo(Location) uses lawOfCosinesDistanceTo(Location). The method preciseDistanceTo(Location) can be used to find a precise distance without selecting haversine or law of cosines specifically. It defaults to law of cosines at the present time.

Relationships between locations can be determined with these methods:

  • headingTo(Location) - The Heading from this location to the given location
  • offsetTo(Location) - The Offset from this location to the given location
  • isClose(Location, Distance) - True if this location is within the given distance of the given location
  • isClose(Location, Angle) - True if the given location's latitude and longitude are within the given angle of this location
Locations support validation via Validatable, and they can be intersected with a rectangle using Intersectable.intersects(Rectangle). Although a location is a zero-dimensional point, it also supports retrieval of a bounding rectangle of zero width and height with Bounded.bounds(). Naturally, a location is also Located for interoperation with other objects that are also Located.

    • equirectangularDistanceBetweenInMillimeters

      public static long equirectangularDistanceBetweenInMillimeters​(long fromLatitudeInDm7, long fromLongitudeInDm7, long toLatitudeInDm7, long toLongitudeInDm7)
      A fast way to compute the distance between two points when the latitude difference is not that much. The formula is essentially the euclidean distance formula (Pythagoras) adjusted by multiplying by cos(latitude), yielding the distance in meters: 
       var x = (lon2 - lon1) * Math.cos(lat1);
 var y = (lat2 - lat1);
 var d = Math.sqrt(x * x + y * y) * EARTH_RADIUS
      The implementation here uses a look-up table for cos(latitude) to improve performance further and returns the result as a long in millimeters instead of as a double in meters.
      Returns:
      The distance in millimeters
      See Also:
      "http://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/latlong.html"

    • asLong

      public long asLong​(Precision precision)
      Returns:
      This location as a single long value, with latitude integer in the high 32 bits and longitude integer value in the low 32 bits. The high and low values are either 6 or 7 decimals. If decimals is 0 (probably due to an uninitialized serialized field), then 6 is assumed to allow for easy defaulting of old 6 decimal graph api values.

    • distanceTo

      public Distance distanceTo​(Location that)
      Computes the distance from this location to the given location. If the latitudinal difference between the two points is close (less than 0.05 degrees, or about 5.5 kilometers), then the faster equirectangularDistanceTo(Location) method is used. When the distance is more than this, the slower but more accurate lawOfCosinesDistanceTo(Location) is used. This gives a nice balance between efficiency and accuracy.
      Returns:
      The distance from this location to the given location

    • equirectangularDistanceTo

      public final Distance equirectangularDistanceTo​(Location that)
      Returns:
      The distance to the given location using an efficient formula consistent with an equirectangular projection. NOTE: This formula is accurate enough for "short" distances (up to a few kilometers), but gets less and less accurate as the latitude difference increases.
      See Also:
      equirectangularDistanceToInMillimeters(Location), equirectangularDistanceBetweenInMillimeters(long, long, long, long)

    • moved

      public Location moved​(Heading heading, Distance offset)
      Given a Location, provide a new Location that is offset a given Distance and Heading. Adapted from: http://www.movable-type.co.uk/scripts/latlong.html See section: "Destination point given distance and bearing from start point"
      Parameters:
      heading - Angle based on the direction of a compass, with 0degree/360degree = North, 90degrees = East, 180 degrees = South, 270 degrees = West.
      offset - Distance from the source point
      Returns:
      The new Location. If this location is on the other side of the -180/180 day separation line, then the Longitudes will be adjusted to be between -180 and 180.
